President Barack Obama delivered remarks at a town hall meeting in Racine, Wisconsin, emphasizing the need for responsible and accountable government that supports the American people. He argued that the nation has a choice between returning to failed economic policies or continuing to build a stronger future. Obama mentioned the comprehensive financial reform being passed to prevent future crises and protect the economy and consumers. He criticized Republicans who opposed this reform, including the leader of the Republicans in the House, who compared the financial crisis to an ant. Obama highlighted the struggles faced by Americans and emphasized the need to prevent such crises from happening again. He also criticized Republicans who opposed raising the limit on what companies like BP have to pay for environmental disasters and the $20 billion fund to compensate those affected by the Gulf oil spill. Obama argued that the government has a responsibility to hold corporations accountable and move the country forward.